 claim. You may get Child Benefit for up to 8 weeks from the date they died.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The longer you leave your claim, the less money you’ll get - so claim as soon as possible.</p>\n</div>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>Make a <a href=\"/child-benefit/how-to-claim\" title=\"Claim Child Benefit\">claim for Child Benefit.</a></p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Attach a note with the date of the child’s death.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Put your contact details and National Insurance number on the note.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Send the child’s birth or adoption certificate with your claim form (you don’t have to send their death certificate).</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Make a claim even if you don&rsquo;t have the birth or adoption certificate - Child Benefit can only be backdated for 3 months. </p>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t have the child&rsquo;s birth or adoption certificate, you can <a href=\"/order-copy-birth-death-marriage-certificate\" title=\"order a new birth or adoption certificate\">order a new one</a> and send it in later.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/changes-affect-child-benefit/one-or-both-parents-die","slug":"one-or-both-parents-die","order":2,"title":"One or both parents die","body":"<p>If you become responsible for a child following the death of their parent or parents you need to:</p>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p><a href=\"https://online.hmrc.gov.uk/shortforms/form/CBO_General?dept-name=CBO&amp;sub-dept-name=General&amp;location=3&amp;origin=http://www.hmrc.gov.uk\" title=\"Report a change of circumstances to the Child Benefit Office\" rel=\"external\">Tell the Child Benefit office</a> straightway - include the exact date of death, where the child is living now and who’s looking after them.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Make a <a href=\"/child-benefit/how-to-claim\" title=\"Claim Child Benefit\">Child Benefit claim</a> for the child (you must do this within 3 months).</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>See if you can claim <a href=\"/guardians-allowance\" title=\"Guardian's Allowance\">Guardian’s Allowance</a> if you’re bringing up someone else’s child or <a href=\"/widowed-parents-allowance\" title=\"Widowed Parent's Allowance\">Widowed Parent’s Allowance</a> if your partner has died.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h2>If your partner dies</h2>\n\n<p>If your partner was getting Child Benefit and has died, you won&rsquo;t get the payments automatically. They&rsquo;ll stop on the Monday after your partner died. </p>\n\n<p>If the payments were going into a bank account that was just in your partner&rsquo;s name you&rsquo;ll need to give the Child Benefit Office a new bank account to pay into.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You’ll need to make a Child Benefit claim even if you were already an ‘alternative payee’ (ie getting Child Benefit paid to you instead of to the person who claimed it).</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re the person getting Child Benefit and your partner has died, the Child Benefit Office will carry on making payments into your bank account. </p>\n\n<h2>If the child and the person getting Child Benefit both die</h2>\n\n<p>You can normally get Child Benefit for 8 weeks after the child has died if this happens. You must have been living with your partner when they died.</p>\n\n<p>Apply for Child Benefit using form CH330A - you can <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://directgov-online.hmrc.gov.uk/shortforms/form/CBO_General?dept-name=CBO&amp;sub-dept-name=General&amp;location=3&amp;origin=http://www.hmrc.gov.uk&amp;lang=eng\" title=\"request form CH330A online\">request this online.</a></p>\n\n<h2>Outstanding Child Benefit</h2>\n\n<p>The Child Benefit Office will also pay any outstanding Child Benefit due to the person who died (called &lsquo;arrears&rsquo;).</p>\n\n<p>To apply for the arrears you must be 16 or over and one of the following:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the executor of the deceased person&rsquo;s estate</li>\n  <li>the person who paid for the funeral</li>\n  <li>the deceased person&rsquo;s next of kin</li>\n  <li>someone who&rsquo;ll spend the money on the children</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You need to apply for the arrears within 12 months of the date the person died. </p>\n\n<p>You can apply for the Child Benefit payments and the arrears using form CH330A. You can <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://directgov-online.hmrc.gov.uk/shortforms/form/CBO_General?dept-name=CBO&amp;sub-dept-name=General&amp;location=3&amp;origin=http://www.hmrc.gov.uk&amp;lang=eng\" title=\"request form CH330A online\">request this online</a> or by calling the Child Benefit Helpline.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Child Benefit Helpline</strong> <br />\nTelephone: 08453 021 444<br />\nTextphone: 08453 021 474 <br />\nMonday to Friday, 8am to 8pm<br />\nSaturday, 8am to 4pm</p>\n</div>\n"}]},"updated_at":"2012-10-22T15:14:50+00:00","tags":[{"title":"Death and bereavement","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages%2Fdeath.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Reporting a death, wills, probate and Inheritance Tax","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=births-deaths-marriages%2Fdeath","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/births-deaths-marriages/death"},"parent":{"title":"Births, deaths, marriages and care","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes civil partnerships, splitting up and Lasting Power of Attorney","short_description":"","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=births-deaths-marriages","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/births-deaths-marriages"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Child Benefit","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages%2Fchild.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Information about eligibility, claiming and when Child Benefit stops","short_description":"","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https:/