es representing the Crown</a> about their estate.</p>\n\n<p>You should only refer an estate if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the person didn&rsquo;t leave a will &ndash; you should try to contact the executor and beneficiaries</li>\n  <li>you tried and failed get in touch with any blood relatives entitled to the estate</li>\n  <li>the person left more funds than debt &ndash; otherwise the estate is &lsquo;insolvent&rsquo;</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>How to refer an estate</h2>\n\n<p>In England and Wales (but not the Duchies of Cornwall or Lancaster), you can <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.bonavacantia.gov.uk/output/deceased-persons-notification-form.aspx\" title=\"refer the estate online\">refer the estate online</a> to the Treasury Solicitor.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The Treasury Solicitor only handles estates worth £500 or more.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>In Scotland, Northern Ireland or the Duchies of Cornwall or Lancaster contact the relevant body representing the Crown. <a href=\"/unclaimed-estates-bona-vacantia/who-to-contact\" title=\"bodies representing the Crown\">body representing the Crown</a>.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/unclaimed-estates-bona-vacantia/grants-from-a-deceased-persons-estate","slug":"grants-from-a-deceased-persons-estate","order":6,"title":"Grants from a deceased person's estate","body":"<p>You can apply for a grant from a deceased person&rsquo;s estate if you could have expected to benefit from it. This could be where:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you provided the person with free services like washing, cleaning, cooking, shopping, home repairs or care where they might otherwise have had to pay</li>\n  <li>you lived together with the person (as their partner or as a friend) but were not married</li>\n  <li>you represent a charity or other body that cared for the person at considerable expense</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You don’t have to be related to the person to apply.</p>\n</div>\n\n